---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Bibliography"
  description="Annotated sources for Nicholas Daly's doctoral research"
  section="research"
>
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1 style="font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 5vw, 3.5rem); font-weight: 400; color: var(--ink); margin-bottom: 0.8rem;">
        <em style="color: var(--red); font-style: italic;">Bibliography</em>
      </h1>
      <div class="page-hero-sub">
        A curated selection of works organized by research strand, with brief annotations of their significance.
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- BIBLIOGRAPHY -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 500; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--ink);">Ecomusicology & Deep Listening</h2>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Pauline Oliveros.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Deep Listening: A Composer's Sound Practice.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">2005.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Foundational text for understanding listening as an active, ethical practice. Oliveros's meditation practices and concept of "deep listening" provide an experiential framework for how students can approach composition with intention and awareness.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">R. Murray Schafer.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">The Soundscape: Our Sonic Environment and the Tuning of the World.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">1977.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Seminal work establishing the concept of soundscape as an ecological entity. Schafer's framework is essential for understanding composition not as isolated creation but as participation in the larger sonic life of the world.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">David Abram.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">The Spell of the Sensuous: Perception and Language in a More-than-Human World.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">1996.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Ecophenomenological approach to sensory perception that grounds music-making in our embodied relationship with the living world. Crucial for understanding the Bestiary's connection to natural patterns and ecological thinking.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Aaron Allen.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Rethinking Ecomusicology: Enacting Post-Romantic Ideologies of Nature in the Age of Ecocriticism.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">2011.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Contemporary ecocritical musicology that challenges romantic idealizations of nature while maintaining attention to the voice of the more-than-human in musical practice.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Christoph Cox & Daniel Warner (eds.).</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Audio Culture: Readings in Modern Music.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">2004.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Comprehensive anthology connecting sonic thought to experimental music practice, including canonical texts and emerging voices in sound studies.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 500; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--ink);">Art / Technology Dialectics</h2>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Bernard Stiegler.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Technics and Time, 1: The Fault of Epimetheus.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">1998.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Foundational text for understanding technology not as external tool but as constitutive of human consciousness. Stiegler's pharmakon concept is crucial for grappling with how algorithms shape compositional thinking.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Ivan Illich.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Tools for Conviviality.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">1973.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Political philosophy of technology that distinguishes between convivial tools (that enhance agency) and alienating ones. Essential for thinking about what makes a pedagogical tool empowering vs. constraining.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Gilles Deleuze & Félix Guattari.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">A Thousand Plateaus: Capitalism and Schizophrenia.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">1987.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Post-structuralist approach to multiplicity and becoming relevant to understanding how creative systems produce novelty. The concept of "smooth vs. striated space" applies to compositional processes.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Don Ihde.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Technology and the Lifeworld: From Garden to Earth.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">1990.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Phenomenological approach to human-technology relations that avoids both techno-utopianism and technophobia. Helpful for thinking about how composers should relate to algorithmic tools.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: none; font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Rob Brandom.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Between Saying and Doing: Towards an Analytic Pragmatism.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">2008.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Contemporary pragmatism that stresses the inseparability of knowledge and practice. Relevant to artistic research methodology and how compositional practice generates knowledge.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 500; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; color: var(--ink);">Practice-Based Research & Pedagogy</h2>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Gert Biesta.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">The Beautiful Risk of Education.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">2014.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Philosophical engagement with education's three purposes: qualification, socialization, and subjectification. Essential for understanding why composition pedagogy must make space for the student's unique voice.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Henk Borgdorff.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">The Conflict of the Faculties: Perspectives on Artistic Research and Academia.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">2012.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Foundational text on artistic research as a legitimate mode of knowledge production. Helps frame the Bestiary as primary research output rather than mere illustration.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Christopher Frayling.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Research in Art and Design.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">1993.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Classic distinction between research "into," "for," and "through" art and design. This research is fundamentally "through"—knowledge is embodied in the artistic practice itself.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-light); font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Linda Candy & Ernest Edmonds.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Practice-Based Research in the Creative Arts: Foundations and Futures from the Front Line.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">2018.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Contemporary overview of practice-based research methodologies in artistic contexts. Provides frameworks for documenting and reflecting on creative work as research.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bib-entry" style="padding: 0.8rem 0; border-bottom: none; font-size: 0.92rem; color: var(--ink-light);">
        <span class="bib-author" style="font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink);">Henry Corbin.</span>
        <span class="bib-title" style="font-style: italic;">Spiritual Body and Celestial Earth: From Mazdean Iran to Shî'ite Iran.</span>
        <span class="bib-year" style="font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size: 0.75rem; color: var(--gold);">1990.</span>
        <p style="margin: 0.3rem 0 0; font-size: 0.85rem;">Corbin's phenomenology of the imaginal world provides theoretical grounding for understanding creativity not as fantasy but as genuine encounter with knowledge. Central to the Bestiary's pedagogical approach.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
